            <div class="section">
                <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">üåø</span>7. √áand (Culture): Kurdish Cuisine</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; margin-bottom: 20px;">Discover the rich culinary traditions of Kurdish culture:</p>
                
                <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fff3e0 0%, #ffe0b2 100%); padding: 30px; border-radius: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border: 3px solid #ffb74d;">
                    <h3 style="color: #e65100; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 25px;">üçΩÔ∏è Xwarina Kurd√Æ (Kurdish Food)</h3>
                    
                    <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #ff9800;">
                        <h4 style="color: #e65100; margin-bottom: 10px;">üçû Nan (Bread) - The Foundation</h4>
                        <p style="line-height: 1.8;">
                            Bread is the most important element of Kurdish cuisine. Traditional Kurdish bread is baked fresh daily in a <strong>tan√ªr</strong> (clay oven). The most common types are <strong>nana tan√ªr√™</strong> (tandoor bread) and <strong>nana t√Ær√Æ</strong> (thin flatbread). Bread is served with every meal and is used to scoop up food.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #ff9800;">
                        <h4 style="color: #e65100; margin-bottom: 10px;">ü•ò Traditional Dishes</h4>
                        <p style="line-height: 1.8;">
                            ‚Ä¢ <strong>Dolma</strong> - Vegetables (peppers, tomatoes, eggplants) stuffed with rice and meat<br>
                            ‚Ä¢ <strong>Kofta</strong> - Spiced meatballs, often served with rice or bulgur<br>
                            ‚Ä¢ <strong>Biryani</strong> - Fragrant rice dish with meat and spices<br>
                            ‚Ä¢ <strong>Yaprax</strong> - Grape leaves stuffed with rice and herbs<br>
                            ‚Ä¢ <strong>Kubba</strong> - Bulgur shells filled with meat and nuts
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #ff9800;">
                        <h4 style="color: #e65100; margin-bottom: 10px;">‚òï √áay (Tea) Culture</h4>
                        <p style="line-height: 1.8;">
                            Tea is the most popular drink in Kurdish culture. It's served throughout the day - morning, afternoon, and evening. Kurdish tea is typically black tea served in small glasses, often sweetened with sugar. Offering tea is a sign of hospitality, and refusing tea can be considered impolite. The phrase <strong>"√áay√™ te p√Æroz be!"</strong> (May your tea be blessed!) is commonly used.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #ff9800;">
                        <h4 style="color: #e65100; margin-bottom: 10px;">üßÄ Pen√Ær √ª Dew (Cheese & Yogurt)</h4>
                        <p style="line-height: 1.8;">
                            Dairy products are essential in Kurdish cuisine. Fresh white cheese (<strong>pen√Ær√™ sp√Æ</strong>) is eaten at breakfast with bread and honey. <strong>Dew</strong> (yogurt drink) is a popular beverage, especially in summer. <strong>Mast</strong> (yogurt) is used in many dishes and sauces.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #ff9800;">
                        <h4 style="color: #e65100; margin-bottom: 10px;">üéâ M√™vandar√Æ (Hospitality)</h4>
                        <p style="line-height: 1.8;">
                            Kurdish hospitality is legendary. Guests are always offered the best food available, and hosts take great pride in serving abundant meals. It's customary to insist that guests eat more, even when they say they're full. The phrase <strong>"N√ª≈ü be!"</strong> (Enjoy your meal!) is said before eating.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

